by self-proclaimed Muslim states
have largely gone backward.

00:18:47.820 --> 00:18:50.660
In the 1990's Nasr Hamid Abu Zayd,

00:18:50.660 --> 00:18:56.620
an Egyptian professor was
judicially declared [inaudible]

00:18:56.620 --> 00:18:59.840
because of his academic writings.

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:06.250
And as a result his marriage to
his Muslim wife was nullified.

00:19:06.250 --> 00:19:10.390
Going back to the Islamic
legal theory, we find no basis

00:19:10.390 --> 00:19:13.470
for the belief in the
immutability of the law

00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:16.040
as interpreted by the schools.

00:19:16.040 --> 00:19:20.350
None of the schools has ever
claimed finality or exclusivity

00:19:20.350 --> 00:19:23.210
of its interpretations of sharia.

00:19:23.210 --> 00:19:29.280
Imam Abu Hanifa [inaudible]
is reported to have said,

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:33.590
our ruling is an opinion,
the best we could attain.

00:19:33.590 --> 00:19:38.060
Whoever comes with a better
option deserves our support.

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:43.340 position:56%
And the Islamic [inaudible] there is
room for different interpretations

00:19:43.340 --> 00:19:51.600 position:56%
to coexist and by extension for such
interpretations to evolve or change.

00:19:51.600 --> 00:19:55.130
In one [inaudible] Prophet
Muhammad is reported to have said,

00:19:55.130 --> 00:19:58.370
the disagreement of my
community is a blessing.

00:19:58.370 --> 00:20:02.290
The Islamic legal theory itself
recognizes the evolving nature

00:20:02.290 --> 00:20:09.730
of Islamic law by adopting the
maxim that states there is denying

00:20:09.730 --> 00:20:13.040
that the changes in times
lead to changes in law.

00:20:13.040 --> 00:20:19.500
It incumbent upon the Muslim
polity to realize that the law

00:20:19.500 --> 00:20:22.750
as formulated by the schools
during the early centuries

00:20:22.750 --> 00:20:26.920
of Islam is not impervious
to change.

00:20:26.920 --> 00:20:30.850
Second, can the sharia support
the new interpretations?

00:20:30.850 --> 00:20:36.100
The universal principles and
values of sharia, such as justice,

00:20:36.100 --> 00:20:41.580
equality, and the public
interest not only support but call

00:20:41.580 --> 00:20:43.000
in my opinion

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:47.330
for new interpretations
of the divine commands.

00:20:47.330 --> 00:20:53.030
[Inaudible], a Muslim scholar who
died around 1316 argues in one

00:20:53.030 --> 00:20:56.230
of his writings that the principle

00:20:56.230 --> 00:21:01.350
of public interest is the ultimate
guide in deriving the legal rules

00:21:01.350 --> 00:21:05.260
of sharia and should be
given precedence even

00:21:05.260 --> 00:21:08.710
over contrary statements
of the divine text.

00:21:08.710 --> 00:21:15.110
In his collection of fataawas
[inaudible] the renowned 14th

00:21:15.110 --> 00:21:18.680
century Muslim scholar
quotes approvingly

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:23.780
that God would support a just
government of unbelievers,

00:21:23.780 --> 00:21:28.630
meaning unMuslims and would not
support an unjust government

00:21:28.630 --> 00:21:31.260
of believers meaning Muslims.

00:21:31.260 --> 00:21:35.760 position:56%
In 1925, Ali Abdel Raziq, a
faculty member of Islamic University

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:40.020
of Al-Azhar published a book
titled, Islam and the Foundation

00:21:40.020 --> 00:21:46.380
of Governance in which he relies
on divine sources to conclude

00:21:46.380 --> 00:21:51.080
that sharia gives the Muslim
polity the right to adopt the form

00:21:51.080 --> 00:21:56.110
of government most
suitable to its needs.

00:21:56.110 --> 00:21:58.470
If the Sunni Muslim polity
ideas with [inaudible]

00:21:58.470 --> 00:22:06.690
and Ali Abdel Raziq there is no
doubt that the political theory

00:22:06.690 --> 00:22:11.230
of the caliphate would undergo a
dramatic reformation from within.

00:22:11.230 --> 00:22:18.240
And lead to the establishment of a
modern government without the need

00:22:18.240 --> 00:22:22.170
for assistance from
us here in the west.

00:22:22.170 --> 00:22:28.140
In the reconstruction of religious
thought Muhammad Iqbal writes the

00:22:28.140 --> 00:22:32.180
republican form of government is
not the only authority consistent

00:22:32.180 --> 00:22:36.470
with the spirit of Islam, but has
also become a necessity in view

00:22:36.470 --> 00:22:41.700
of the new forces that are
set free in the word of Islam.

00:22:41.700 --> 00:22:46.560
Because of his belief in
the compatibility of Islam

00:22:46.560 --> 00:22:52.220
with modern government Sheikh
Muhammad Abdu, the great reformer

00:22:52.220 --> 00:22:58.740
of the 19th century has allegedly
said after visiting friends.

00:22:58.740 --> 00:23:04.860
In France I saw Islam
I didn't see Muslims.

00:23:04.860 --> 00:23:10.050
In Egypt I see Muslims
I don't see Islam.

00:23:10.050 --> 00:23:15.820
My colleagues on this
panel may have more to say

00:23:15.820 --> 00:23:18.630
about how specific interpretations

00:23:18.630 --> 00:23:24.060
of sharia would support
through reformation.

00:23:24.060 --> 00:23:29.820
Third, who has the authority
to reform Islamic law?

00:23:29.820 --> 00:23:34.210
To answer this question we need
to go back to the formative period

00:23:34.210 --> 00:23:40.610
and find out how the work of the
various schools was legitimized

00:23:40.610 --> 00:23:44.250
into becoming a binding law.

00:23:44.250 --> 00:23:48.310
The schools did not have any
authority in this regard.

00:23:48.310 --> 00:23:53.710 position:56%
None of the schools had any official
status, representative capacity

00:23:53.710 --> 00:23:59.570
or legislative mandate to decide
on what the law is or isn't.

00:23:59.570 --> 00:24:02.990
They all came into existence
on their own initiative

00:24:02.990 --> 00:24:06.420
and acted independently
from and at times

00:24:06.420 --> 00:24:09.200
in confrontation with the state.

00:24:09.200 --> 00:24:14.620
The authority that legitimized
the law as formulated

00:24:14.620 --> 00:24:19.980
by the schools was the
authority of the Muslim people.

00:24:19.980 --> 00:24:24.930
Schools that did not garner the
consent of the people disappeared

00:24:24.930 --> 00:24:31.220
and their interpretations of the
divine commands never became law.

00:24:31.220 --> 00:24:35.460
Among the many schools that came
into existence only the work

00:24:35.460 --> 00:24:42.420
of a few got the support
needed to become binding law.

00:24:42.420 --> 00:24:46.120
The authority of the Muslim
polity as the legitimizing factor

00:24:46.120 --> 00:24:53.330 position:56%
of Islamic law has been enshrined in
the doctrine of Ijma or consensus.

00:24:53.330 --> 00:24:58.510
And that this doctrine the
consensus of the Muslim polity

00:24:58.510 --> 00:25:01.750
on a legal matter not
only legitimizes

00:25:01.750 --> 00:25:07.230 position:56%
that legal rule resulting therefrom,
but constitutes an original source

00:25:07.230 --> 00:25:10.830
of the legal rules themselves.

00:25:10.830 --> 00:25:17.660
As a consequence, the Muslim polity
not the Muslim scholars has the

00:25:17.660 --> 00:25:21.820
authority to reform Islamic law.

00:25:21.820 --> 00:25:28.110
In concluding, it is
reasonable to wonder

00:25:28.110 --> 00:25:34.840
if the Islamic legal theory
allows for the reformation

00:25:34.840 --> 00:25:37.800
of Islamic law from within.

00:25:37.800 --> 00:25:43.130
Why haven't such reformations
materialized?

00:25:43.130 --> 00:25:47.990
The essence of the answer
given by Muhammed Iqbal early

00:25:47.990 --> 00:25:52.970
in the last century is
probably still valid today.

00:25:52.970 --> 00:25:58.560
The conservative Muslim public
is still not yet quite ready

00:25:58.560 --> 00:26:04.290
for a critical discussion of the
past interpretation of sharia.

00:26:04.290 --> 00:26:06.510
Thank you very much.

00:26:06.510 --> 00:26:23.140
[ Applause ]

00:26:23.140 --> 00:26:27.260
&gt;&gt; Kristen A. Stilt: Thank you to
Dr. Saliba and to Kimberly Zellars

00:26:27.260 --> 00:26:30.850
and everyone here at the Library
of Congress for this invitation

00:26:30.850 --> 00:26:34.390
to be here on or in honor of
I should say Human Rights Day.

00:26:34.390 --> 00:26:37.100
We have a few more days until
Human Rights Day itself.

00:26:37.100 --> 00:26:41.240
I am very pleased to be here with
such distinguished colleagues.

00:26:41.240 --> 00:26:47.220 position:56%
And today I'll be focusing on family
law in this short presentation.

00:26:47.220 --> 00:26:51.280
So family law in Muslim majority
countries has undergone tremendous

00:26:51.280 --> 00:26:55.380
change over the past century
and this change continues today

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:58.070
with intensity and controversy.

00:26:58.070 --> 00:27:00.110
And change can happen in many ways

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:03.140
and can be led by many
types of actors.

00:27:03.140 --> 00:27:06.990
But today I'm talking about
when actors such as legislators

00:27:06.990 --> 00:27:11.650 position:56%
or activists or monarchs want to
change family law with the intention

00:27:11.650 --> 00:27:14.740
of improving the rights
of women and children.

00:27:14.740 --> 00:27:19.840
And in general, this change has
sought to adopt national laws

00:27:19.840 --> 00:27:24.470 position:56%
that would modify the rules of
Islamic law that had been applicable

00:27:24.470 --> 00:27:27.870
and predominant in that
particular country.

00:27:27.870 --> 00:27:30.440
And these efforts and
I'll call them reforms

00:27:30.440 --> 00:27:35.080
because that's the term the
actors use themselves have focused

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:37.600
on a number of areas in particular.

00:27:37.600 --> 00:27:43.300
So substantively, these efforts
have aimed at placing restrictions

00:27:43.300 --> 00:27:46.850
on a husband's right to enter
into a polygamous marriage,

00:27:46.850 --> 00:27:48.410
limiting a husband's right

00:27:48.410 --> 00:27:52.780 position:56%
to unilaterally declare his wife
divorced, extending a mother's right

00:27:52.780 --> 00:27:56.350
to custody of the children
and be compensated for it

00:27:56.350 --> 00:28:00.160
by her ex-husband, raising
the minimum marriage age,

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:04.440
expanding a wife's ability to get
a divorce at her own initiative

00:28:04.440 --> 00:28:06.960
and requiring a husband
to compensate his wife

00:28:06.960 --> 00:28:08.870
if he arbitrarily divorces her.

00:28:08.870 --> 00:28:13.490 position:56%
So in some Muslim majority countries
and we'll take Turkey as the example

00:28:13.490 --> 00:28:16.970
of this, major modification of
the family law have been made

00:28:16.970 --> 00:28:20.340
by essentially adopting
secular codes.

00:28:20.340 --> 00:28:25.130
In doing so in Turkey for example,
Turkey operated in the context

00:28:25.130 --> 00:28:28.730
of its form of secularism as
enshrined in its constitution

00:28:28.730 --> 00:28:32.780
and did not attempt to justify
any of its changes as compatible

00:28:32.780 --> 00:28:34.830
with Islamic law in any way.

00:28:34.830 --> 00:28:37.690
But in most Muslim
majority countries,

00:28:37.690 --> 00:28:40.750
the rules of Islamic law
are particularly relevant

00:28:40.750 --> 00:28:42.690
in the area of family law.

00:28:42.690 --> 00:28:46.260
And so the change process or
the reform process takes place

00:28:46.260 --> 00:28:51.170 position:56%
within this space and changes are
presented as taking place internally

00:28:51.170 --> 00:28:54.480
to Islamic law rather than
something external to it.

00:28:54.480 --> 00:28:56.890
So just to be clear
what I mean by that.

00:28:56.890 --> 00:29:00.050
This may be in a country for
which religious law is not part

00:29:00.050 --> 00:29:03.110
of other areas of the law like
business law or criminal law

00:29:03.110 --> 00:29:07.090
or international law, but family
law often remains a domain

00:29:07.090 --> 00:29:09.400
where there's a belief
that it is Islamic law

00:29:09.400 --> 00:29:11.090
and that it should remain that way.

00:29:11.090 --> 00:29:14.760
That belief is somewhat problematic
and we can talk about that later.

00:29:14.760 --> 00:29:18.820
So the reasons for this internal
approach range from faith-based

00:29:18.820 --> 00:29:23.850 position:56%
to pragmatic, including the personal
beliefs of advocates and lawmakers

00:29:23.850 --> 00:29:27.870
and concerns over the lack of
popular acceptance of a family law

00:29:27.870 --> 00:29:32.080
that appears to be western
or secular in origin.

00:29:32.080 --> 00:29:36.120
And so my talk today will focus
very briefly on two changes

00:29:36.120 --> 00:29:39.830
in Sunni family law and how
those changes have been presented

00:29:39.830 --> 00:29:42.120
or justified to strategies.

00:29:42.120 --> 00:29:47.040
My focus in this project from which
this short presentation is derived

00:29:47.040 --> 00:29:50.630
is focused mainly on the Arab
Sunni world, but we can talk beyond

00:29:50.630 --> 00:29:52.440
that later if you would like.

00:29:52.440 --> 00:29:55.160
So one when more preliminary
comment.

00:29:55.160 --> 00:29:58.070
I think we want to think and
talk about what is gained

00:29:58.070 --> 00:30:01.350
and what is lost when family
law in a country is seen

00:30:01.350 --> 00:30:04.570
as the exclusive domain
of Islamic law.

00:30:04.570 --> 00:30:09.420
It tends to mean that when an
advocacy organization sees a social

00:30:09.420 --> 00:30:12.110
need for a change they
have to carefully think

00:30:12.110 --> 00:30:15.280
about whether they can
justify it in Islamic terms.

00:30:15.280 --> 00:30:17.700
But of course if they can
the potential for acceptance

00:30:17.700 --> 00:30:20.420
of the change can be much higher.

00:30:20.420 --> 00:30:23.170
But, of course, many of these
countries have signed international

00:30:23.170 --> 00:30:26.780
human rights treaties, such as
the convention on the elimination

00:30:26.780 --> 00:30:30.560
of all forms of discrimination
against women or CEDAW.

00:30:30.560 --> 00:30:35.520
Although, sometimes they have put
reservations with those treaties.

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:38.700
And advocacy groups might be
very active in conversations

00:30:38.700 --> 00:30:41.590
about human rights treaties
like CEDAW and see them

00:30:41.590 --> 00:30:44.880
as setting important
benchmarks or goals.

00:30:44.880 --> 00:30:47.980
But is the fact that a
country's laws are not compatible

00:30:47.980 --> 00:30:52.720
with CEDAW off for example, on its
own enough to garner the initiative

00:30:52.720 --> 00:30:55.510
to change the law and
that's the big question.

00:30:55.510 --> 00:30:58.850
And the answer is probably
not for many places.

00:30:58.850 --> 00:31:01.930
An exhaustive study
of Morocco and Jordan

00:31:01.930 --> 00:31:05.100
that a scholar has just
completed she noted quote,

00:31:05.100 --> 00:31:08.980
despite women's groups questioning
that family law should be

00:31:08.980 --> 00:31:13.720
or indeed is Islamic law publicly,
they still have to recognize

00:31:13.720 --> 00:31:17.600
that family law is Islamic law,
which limits the possible arguments

00:31:17.600 --> 00:31:20.400
that can be used to
advance their claims.

00:31:20.400 --> 00:31:24.310
So with that background I just
want to cover two areas of the law

00:31:24.310 --> 00:31:25.700
and show you what the change was

00:31:25.700 --> 00:31:28.740
and then how it was
justified in Islamic terms.

00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:32.130
And the first one is polygamy

00:31:32.130 --> 00:31:36.190
and the strategy that's been
used is essentially taking powers

00:31:36.190 --> 00:31:39.510
that were left in the hands of
individuals and the husbands

00:31:39.510 --> 00:31:44.070
in particular and assigning
that power to a judge.

00:31:44.070 --> 00:31:48.960
So few Muslim majority countries
have abolished polygamy as a matter

00:31:48.960 --> 00:31:54.600
of national law, but most attempt
to curtail the rights of a husband

00:31:54.600 --> 00:31:57.280 position:56%
to enter into a polygamous marriage.

00:31:57.280 --> 00:31:59.590
And they place emphasis
on the Quranic verse

00:31:59.590 --> 00:32:02.910
that requires equitable
treatment among wives.

00:32:02.910 --> 00:32:07.740
Quote, then marry from among other
women, such as are lawful to you,

00:32:07.740 --> 00:32:10.480
two, three or four, but
if you have reason to fear

00:32:10.480 --> 00:32:12.070
that you might not
be able to treat them

00:32:12.070 --> 00:32:14.480
with equal fairness that only one.

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:19.450
And that verse seems to speak
to a man and cautions him.

00:32:19.450 --> 00:32:24.140
Yet another verse says, no it's
not possible to do that quote

00:32:24.140 --> 00:32:26.590
and it will not be within
your power to treat your wives

00:32:26.590 --> 00:32:30.010
with equal fairness,
however, you may desire it.

00:32:30.010 --> 00:32:33.940
And so do not allow yourselves
to incline towards the exclusion

00:32:33.940 --> 00:32:38.020
to one exclusion of the other
leaving her in a state of having

00:32:38.020 --> 00:32:39.320
and not having a husband.

00:32:39.320 --> 00:32:40.660
I just paraphrased there.

00:32:40.660 --> 00:32:45.700 position:56%
So many countries have adopted laws
that essentially require the husband

00:32:45.700 --> 00:32:49.630
to go to the judge and
not leave that decision

00:32:49.630 --> 00:32:53.050
about equal treatment
up to the individual.

00:32:53.050 --> 00:32:59.300
Morocco adopted this approach
in 2004 in its family law code

00:32:59.300 --> 00:33:01.490
that many you might
be familiar with.

00:33:01.490 --> 00:33:05.030
In the preamble the Moroccan king
said he would not allow outlaw

00:33:05.030 --> 00:33:08.800
polygamy due to his belief
that it is permissible.

00:33:08.800 --> 00:33:12.800
But he said that polygamous
marriages would only be allowed

00:33:12.800 --> 00:33:17.010
under compelling circumstances
and stringent restrictions

00:33:17.010 --> 00:33:19.860
with the judge's authorization.

00:33:19.860 --> 00:33:23.480
The judge must verify that
the husband has the means

00:33:23.480 --> 00:33:27.000
and there must be an exceptional
mode of justifying polygamy

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:31.280
and this perspective second
wife must know and must consent

00:33:31.280 --> 00:33:33.870
to the polygamist marriage.

00:33:33.870 --> 00:33:39.830
Most recently in Jordan the
Jordanian Women's Union officially

00:33:39.830 --> 00:33:42.340
opposed polygamy, but
they were afraid

00:33:42.340 --> 00:33:46.100
that they wouldn't achieve
that in the 2010 law.

00:33:46.100 --> 00:33:50.590
And so they instead proposed
judicial oversight along the same

00:33:50.590 --> 00:33:53.170
lines as what was done in Morocco.

00:33:53.170 --> 00:33:57.410
So notice how this strategy
works, it does not attempt

00:33:57.410 --> 00:34:01.450
to declare polygamy impermissible
or even illegal in the state,

00:34:01.450 --> 00:34:06.160
but instead uses those verses
to say to the husband more

00:34:06.160 --> 00:34:09.680
or less we don't think you're
the one that should decide

00:34:09.680 --> 00:34:12.680
and the judge will
be the one to do it.

00:34:12.680 --> 00:34:15.240
But I should note that even
that strategy has been seen

00:34:15.240 --> 00:34:18.810
as too controversial
in some countries.

00:34:18.810 --> 00:34:21.860
So the next area, the second
area quickly is the area

00:34:21.860 --> 00:34:23.160
of marriage contracts.

00:34:23.160 --> 00:34:27.510
And the strategy here is something
I call encouraging the permissible.

00:34:27.510 --> 00:34:31.260
So this strategy recognizes
that a gap exists

00:34:31.260 --> 00:34:34.800
between what's permissible
as a matter of Islamic law

00:34:34.800 --> 00:34:40.110
and what reformers think they can
actually require as state law.

00:34:40.110 --> 00:34:44.060
And so they try to approximate
state law by encouraging people

00:34:44.060 --> 00:34:47.030
to take advantage of
options they already have.

00:34:47.030 --> 00:34:50.680
And so on one level this is sort
of like know your rights campaign,

00:34:50.680 --> 00:34:55.570
but the more you can encourage
something the more it would be

00:34:55.570 --> 00:34:59.800
potentially taken up by individuals
the more you can approximate

00:34:59.800 --> 00:35:01.940
something like national law.

00:35:01.940 --> 00:35:05.680
And so a good example of
this comes from Jordan.

00:35:05.680 --> 00:35:10.060
So marriage contracts can contain
additional stipulations as long

00:35:10.060 --> 00:35:14.270
as they don't undercut the
essence of the contract itself.

00:35:14.270 --> 00:35:17.470
So the Jordanian laws of 1976

00:35:17.470 --> 00:35:22.890
and 2010 specifically
identify conditions or clauses

00:35:22.890 --> 00:35:25.900
in the contract that are
considered acceptable

00:35:25.900 --> 00:35:28.980
and would be upheld
by a Jordanian court.

00:35:28.980 --> 00:35:32.260
These include for example,
requiring the husband not

00:35:32.260 --> 00:35:35.730
to take another wife, not to
prevent the wife from working,

00:35:35.730 --> 00:35:38.860
not to require her to move
to a place she doesn't want

00:35:38.860 --> 00:35:41.760
and giving her the right
to divorce herself.

00:35:41.760 --> 00:35:45.660
And so the activists felt that
they were not able to achieve

00:35:45.660 --> 00:35:48.340
that as a matter of
national law for example,

00:35:48.340 --> 00:35:50.080
without anything else spoken

00:35:50.080 --> 00:35:53.330
about in the contract the
husband do those things.

00:35:53.330 --> 00:35:57.250
But by mentioning these in the
law there's an implicit statement,

00:35:57.250 --> 00:36:00.260
you can do this, you can
put this into your contract

